  "prompt": "What is the present Infant Mortality Rate (IMR) of Nepal? What is the government doing to improve it?",
  "response": "As of my last knowledge update in October 2023, the most recent data indicated that Nepal's Infant Mortality Rate (IMR) was approximately 26 deaths per 1,000 live births. However, please note that this figure may have changed since then, and it is advisable to consult the latest reports from organizations such as the World Bank, UNICEF, or the Nepalese government for the most current statistics.\n\nTo improve the IMR, the Nepalese government has implemented several measures, including:\n\n1. **Enhanced Healthcare Services**: Increasing access to healthcare facilities, particularly in rural areas, to ensure that mothers and infants receive necessary medical attention.\n\n2. **Maternal and Child Health Programs**: Initiatives aimed at improving maternal health, including antenatal care, skilled birth attendance, and postnatal care.\n\n3. **Vaccination Campaigns**: Expanding immunization coverage to protect infants from preventable diseases.\n\n4. **Nutrition Programs**: Addressing malnutrition among mothers and infants through various nutritional support programs.\n\n5. **Community Health Workers**: Training and deploying community health workers to provide education and support to families about maternal and infant health.\n\n6. **Public Awareness Campaigns**: Raising awareness about the importance of healthcare practices, nutrition, and hygiene.\n\n7. **Partnerships with NGOs and International Organizations**: Collaborating with various organizations to implement health programs and share resources.\n\nFor the most accurate and up-to-date information, please refer to the latest health reports or government publications.",
